It was written during the Cold War, and large portions of the background material and worldbuilding were, if not exactly stolen, then obvious references to and respectful homages to 20th Century pulp sci-fi. Square-jawed Tough Guys with cigarettes hanging out of their mouths staring at the instrument panels of their spaceships, which were covered in analog dials like the control panel of a B-17, lots of hardcases with ray-guns on their hips stepping down the gangplank onto the surface of a newly discovered jungle world. It was very two-fisted pulp adventure flavored, but in space.

Traveller. The wolf-derived sophont species are the Vargr. They are not cute and fuzzy. They are as intelligent as humans but do not think like humans. Due to their pack-oriented social structure, they cooperate as small groups that have regular contact with a charismatic pack alpha, and being genetically manipulated carnivores, they don't have nearly so many inhibitions about violence as humans tend to, as a general rule, in the aggregate. One of the things this means is that piracy and banditry are very common among them, and that's how humans made first contact with them centuries back. There were countless tiny incidents and several large-scale wars, and lots of people on both sides are still very upset with the other side about it. Of course there are many nations and cultures and factions among the Vargr, too, and they're every bit as cruel to each other as they are to non-Vargr. They are constantly at war with one another, constantly raiding one another for slaves and loot. Individual Vargr can be very good friends and are hardwired to be extremely loyal to those around them they perceive to be their pack, even if they're other species. >Russian type III AK with no indents
It's a Romanian WASR10, unless I miss my guess. Stamped AKM type receiver without the dimples, with little brackets tack welded inside on either side instead. Due to some retarded US laws they have to be imported in muh "sporting rifle" configuration with thumbhole stocks and the mag well cut for a proprietary singlestack mag that can't be readily found here, then CNC milled to accept a proper AK mag. The bolt has a narrow lug on the bottom to strip the cartridges off the top of the proprietary magazine that always holds them in the center, but it does not seem to impede function with proper AK mags. Also, there are a number of slabside AK mags, or maybe he just didn't draw the ridges.

Anonymous Thu 08 Dec 2022 05:01:07 No.52886963 Report

>>52886841
Nuclear weapons are extremely maintenance-intensive. The radioactive material they contain causes things to begin to break down and oxidize in proximity to them. The electronics, the explosive charges that are supposed to assemble the critical mass at the moment of detonation, everything. Ask any Air Force "glowworm" with a 2W series MOS--or don't, because I am pretty sure specifics are still classified. Nation-states are able to hire and train large numbers of specialists who check this stuff and replace parts that have gone bad so the bombs will be ready to go if needed. It's not like a crate of grenades that could have been put on a pallet in an ammo bunker in 1947 and is still perfect 75 years later. The resources required are beyond most individuals' capabilities. Though I suppose that if Elon Musk wanted his own nuclear deterrent, it might be doable for him.

Here we get into aspects of the social contract that are not often examined, even by lawyers. What is a right? Rights are the obligations that the state has towards the citizen. Citizens have duties, and these are the obligations of the citizen to the state. In any society there may be individuals who are not party to the social contract. Convicted felons, for example. Convicted felons are individuals who have behaved in a manner that amounts to waging war on society and as a result have been stripped of their citizenship. Compare the Norse concepts of utlagr and níðingr, men whose behavior had put them outside the law and were not entitled to the law's protections. They're not supposed to have a say in how society makes its decisions. They're not supposed to be able to vote, for example.

But the other elephant in the room is that, at least in the US, there is an entire branch of government created to interpret and apply the law. In civics class they call this the judicial branch. Almost all of them are appointed for life. There are essentially no checks on what they can do. As a practical matter it is almost impossible to remove one from office for any act short of getting caught with CP. They are little kings in black robes and they hand out whatever diktats they want with smirks on their faces, and the Boys in Blue, a.k.a. the Badge & Gun Gang, will happily carry out their orders, no matter how whimsical. The worst that can happen is that one of their fiats can be overturned by a judge in a higher court, but as a practical matter that usually takes decades if it happens at all. The Constitution is essentially irrelevant and has been going back to the Civil War. The law is whatever the judge says it is today, and they are no longer pretending they aren't making it all up as they go along.
